SIMPLE: hoot
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hoot
<hw>Hoot</hw> <pr>(h⟦oomac⟧t)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Hooted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Hooting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>hoten</ets>,
<ets>houten</ets>, <ets>huten</ets>; cf. OSw. <ets>huta</ets>, Sw.
<ets>huta ut</ets> to take one up sharply, fr. Sw. <ets>hut</ets>
interj., begone! cf. also W. <ets>hwt</ets> off! off with it! away!
hoot!]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cry out or shout in contempt.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Matrons and girls shall <qex>hoot</qex> at thee no more.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make the peculiar cry of an owl.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The clamorous owl that nightly <qex>hoots</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hoot</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hoot
<hw>Hoot</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To assail with contemptuous cries
or shouts; to follow with derisive shouts.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Partridge and his clan may <qex>hoot</qex> me for a cheat.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hoot</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Hoot
<hw>Hoot</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A derisive cry or
shout.</def> <rj><au>Glanvill.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The cry of an owl.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A very funny event, person, or experience; <as>as,
watching Jack try to catch that greased pig was a
<ex>hoot</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Hoot owl</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the barred owl
(<spn>Syrnium nebulosum</spn>). See <er>Barred owl</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>not give a hoot</b></col> <cd>not care at all.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hoot down</ent>⟦br⟧
